I like it, but that last note makes me hesitant to upvote. It seems like an especially extreme super-serious consequences addenda. Its presence in the article, from an in-universe point of view, could only possibly serve to do more harm than good; that this rumor is explicitly denied, when there are surely others, seems to lend credibility to it. If it's so vital that the message not be sent, I'm not sure it's wise to give any indications whatsoever as to what the message may or may not be.

It's kinda like the US policy on nuclear secrets, and leaks thereof. Acknowledge a leak, or take steps to cover it up, and you're giving credibility to the information and confirming it as accurate to some degree. If it isn't accurate anyway, then there's nothing to be gained by saying it's not. The Foundation already knows what String 17 contained and therefore will contain. Inaccurate rumors about its contents are likely to push its date of transmission back further.







